lavatsky's The Voice of the Silence -- tIV The Stages of Initiation In-between "Hinduism" and Theosophical Evolutionism -- tIntroduction -- t10 The Reception of "Hinduism" in the Theosophical Society: Encounters in the Indian Middle Class -- t11 Manilal Dvivedi, the Forgotten "Expert" on "Hinduism" -- t12 T. Subba Row, the "Expert" on "Hinduism" -- tV The "Quickening of Evolution" 2: The Pedagogy of Morality Based on the Stages of Initiation -- tIntroduction -- t13 The "Quickening of Evolution": Education for Initiation in the Central Hindu College and the Sanâtana Dharma Text Books -- t14 Conclusion -- tBibliography -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tHistorical Persons Index -- tPerson Index -- tPublications Index -- tSubjects Index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe main subjects of analysis in the present book are the stages of initiation in the grand scheme of Theosophical evolution. These initiatory steps are connected to an idea of evolutionary self-development by means of a set of virtues that are relative to the individual's position on the path of evolution. The central thesis is that these stages were translated from the "Hindu" tradition to the "Theosophical" tradition through multifaceted "hybridization processes" in which several Indian members of the Theosophical Society partook. Starting with Annie Besant's early Theosophy, the stages of initiation are traced through Blavatsky's work to Manilal Dvivedi and T. Subba Row, both Indian members of the Theosophical Society, and then on to the Sanâtana Dharma Text Books. In 1898, the English Theosophist Annie Besant and the Indian Theosophist Bhagavan Das together founded the Central Hindu College, Benares, which became the nucleus around which the Benares Hindu University was instituted in 1915. In this context the Sanâtana Dharma Text Books were published. Mühlematter shows that the stages of initiation were the blueprint for Annie Besant's pedagogy, which she implemented in the Central Hindu College in Benares. In doing so, he succeeds in making intelligible how "esoteric" knowledge was transferred to public institutions and how a broader public could be reached as a result. The dissertation has been awarded the ESSWE PhD Thesis prize 2022 by the European Society for the Study of Western Esotericism.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Schweizer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 4aEsoterik. 4aPostkolonialismus. 4aReligionswissenschaft. 4aTheosophie. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aReligious studies.  aesotericism.  apostcolonialism.  atheosophy.2 aSchweizer Nationalfonds (SNF)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd0 cEPUBz97831107947930 cprintz978311079456440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110794694zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110794694zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110794694/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA